{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657611","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657611"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20583"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20583"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[1,0,0,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93733"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13460"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76943"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12503"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32143"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93733","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93733"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAortic dissection is a life-threatening condition characterised by separation of the layers of the aortic wall. Various risk factors contribute to the development of this condition, with one factor being particularly predominant.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most significant risk factor for aortic dissection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hypertension","Diabetes mellitus","Hypercholesterolaemia","Cigarette smoking","Obesity"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertension\u003C/strong\u003E is the most significant risk factor for aortic dissection, present in approximately 75-80% of cases. Chronic elevation in blood pressure leads to increased mechanical stress on the aortic wall, promoting medial degeneration and weakening of the vessel wall structure. This weakening predisposes the aorta to intimal tears, allowing blood to enter the medial layer and create a false lumen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less significant risk factors:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E is not a major risk factor for aortic dissection. Some studies suggest it may actually have a protective effect against aortic aneurysm formation and dissection, possibly due to increased collagen cross-linking in the vessel wall.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypercholesterolaemia\u003C/strong\u003E contributes to atherosclerosis but is not a primary risk factor for aortic dissection. While atherosclerosis can weaken the vessel wall, it does not have as direct a relationship with dissection as hypertension.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECigarette smoking\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with aortic disease, including aneurysm formation, but its contribution to aortic dissection risk is significantly less than that of hypertension.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObesity\u003C/strong\u003E may indirectly increase risk through its association with hypertension, but it is not considered an independent primary risk factor for aortic dissection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther significant risk factors for aortic dissection include connective tissue disorders (such as Marfan syndrome and Ehlers-Danlos syndrome), bicuspid aortic valve, family history, pregnancy (particularly in the third trimester), and iatrogenic causes (such as catheterisation procedures).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypertension is the most significant risk factor for aortic dissection, present in 75-80% of cases.","Aortic dissection occurs when blood enters the medial layer through an intimal tear, creating a false lumen.","Chronic hypertension causes medial degeneration and weakening of the aortic wall, predisposing to dissection."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 11; pages 507"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76943"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20583"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76943"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T09:25:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T09:30:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13460"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93733"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood vessels","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12503"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Aortic dissection","synonyms":[